The claim here, as I understand it, is that game development is expensive, but sequels are cheaper than originals because developers can just reuse the "code and graphics" from the previous game. That's a common misconception. A triple-A sequel isn't typically cheaper to make than the original, but they are (perceived to be) less risky. I've added some references to this effect. I think the Shacknews reference should be removed because it's old. BBC is a more reliable source so I'd leave it.
